properties.Title: Update To Civil Emergency Alert Issued By Government Of Saskatchewan
properties.Summary:
Description: Update for the Civil Emergency Alert issued by the Government of Saskatchewan. The state of emergency in Saskatchewan remains in effect. UPDATE: Phase 2 of Re-Open Saskatchewan is effective May 19, 2020. All Public Health Orders continue to apply during the implementation of Phase 2 Re-Open Saskatchewan. People are being reminded to avoid unnecessary travel and stay home if you are sick or symptomatic. Public and private gatherings, inside and outside, are limited to more no more than 10 people and physical distancing by at least two metres from others is to be applied. Monitor and follow all public health orders on the Saskatchewan.ca COVID 19 website. Wash your hands often. Together, we are reducing the risk. We can pull together by staying apart.
Expires: 2020-05-25T17:00:00-06:00
Originated from CAP Alert: SK Provincial Emergency Communications Centre, 2020-05-19T16:41:35-06:00, 3EA4278A-7E10-0E3D-2DB2-71CB93B8F62A
Area: Province of Saskatchewan
properties.Author: SK Provincial Emergency Communications Centre

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A system tracking across Hudson Bay is expected to bring snow and strong northwesterly winds to the Naujaat area. Snow associated with this system will move into the region this evening with 5 to 10 cm falling by morning. In its wake strong northwesterly winds will develop on Wednesday resulting in blizzard conditions by Wednesday night. Blizzard conditions will likely persist on Thursday but ease by Friday morning. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2020-05-20T11:47:08-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-05-19T19:48:08-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.3639861459.2020
Area: Naujaat

properties.Title: Frost Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Frost may damage some crops in frost-prone areas. Minimum temperatures: minus 3 in low lying areas to plus 3 along parts of the coast. Locations: Prince Edward Island. Time span: overnight and early Wednesday morning. Remarks: frost is expected to form again tonight as clear skies and light winds coincide with cool temperatures, especially in low lying areas. ### Frost advisories are issued when temperatures are expected to reach the freezing mark during the growing season, leading to potential damage and destruction to plants and crops. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to PEstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #PEStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Snow and strong northerly winds are expected to result in blizzard conditions in the Sanirajak (Hall Beach) region beginning Wednesday morning. These blizzard conditions will likely persist into Wednesday night before improving Thursday morning. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 15 to 25 cm is expected. Heavy snow expected in Pangnirtung Wednesday into Wednesday night. Heavy snow will move into the Pangnirtung region Wednesday morning and continue into Wednesday night. Total snowfall accumulations of 15 to 25 cm are possible by Thursday morning. Periods of light snow may persist in the region on Thursday however no further significant accumulation are expected. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. A low pressure system tracking through Hudson Bay will bring a wintery mix of weather to communities in southern Baffin Island beginning tonight and persisting into Thursday. The area will see snow develop tonight changing over or becoming mixed with freezing rain or rain by Thursday morning. On Thursday cold air behind the system will work its way eastward changing the precipitation back to snow throughout the course of the day. In addition, in the wake of the front, gusty westerly winds will be a concern especially at Kinngait where a wind warning is currently in effect. Winds here may gust to over 100 km/h beginning Wednesday afternoon with gusts to 70 possible in Kimmirut Wednesday afternoon. Please stay alert for updated bulletins as the weather story may change as the system approaches Baffin Island. Refer to public forecasts for additional details. ### Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2020-05-20T12:20:03-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-05-19T20:21:03-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0341375915.2020
Area: Iqaluit, Kimmirut, Cape Dorset

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A strengthening winter storm moving across Hudson Bay will spread heavy snow into Coral Harbour late this afternoon. The snow may be heavy at times and possibley mixed with freezing rain. The precipitation will persist through the night before easing Wednesday morning. In addition to the snow, strong northerly winds of 60 gusting 80 km/h will develop overnight, resulting in poor visibilities in blowing and falling snow. The strong winds will persist through Wednesday and much of Thursday and may result in near blizzard conditions. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Severe westerly winds will develop in the Kinngait region today. Winds will shift to the west in Kinngait later this morning and strengthen into the 70 to 80 km/h range with gusts potentially exceeding 100 km/h. These severe winds will persist into the evening and then ease slightly to 60 gusting 80 km/h for Wednesday night and Thursday. Visibilities may be reduced in blowing snow at times. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
